    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "We can use the fact that the number of divisors of a number i is equal to the product of the powers of its prime factors plus one. We can calculate the prime factorization of i and then calculate the number of divisors.\n\n```python\ndef prime_factors(n):\n    factors = {}\n    i = 2\n    while i * i <= n:\n        if n % i:\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            n //= i\n            factors[i] = factors.get(i, 0) + 1\n    if n > 1:\n        factors[n] = factors.get(n, 0) + 1\n    return factors\n\ndef count_divisors(n):\n    factors = prime_factors(n)\n    count = 1\n    for factor in factors.values():\n        count *= (factor + 1)\n    return count\n\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    return sum(count_divisors(i) for i in range(1, n + 1))\n```\n\nThis function first calculates the prime factorization of i, then calculates the number of divisors by multiplying together the powers of its prime factors plus one. This approach has a time complexity of O(n log log n) due to the prime",
